Loading the data

Correlation of response variables:

Symbionts and growth:

In coral biology, we generally assume more symbionts -> more photosynthetic carbon. Therefore, wed expect that more symbionts -> more growth. In some cases, symbiont populations can become parasitic and hoard resources for themselves. This has been shown at much higher levels of symbionts than seen in this experiment (1-3 x 10^6). So, wed traditionally expect that more symbionts would lead to higher coral growth. Except.

Percent change in buoyant weight is related to symbiont population only in Porites rus, not in Pocillopora acuta:

## # A tibble: 2  4
##   Species           P_Value Marginal_R2 Conditional_R2
##   <chr>               <dbl>       <dbl>          <dbl>
## 1 Pocillopora acuta  0.914     0.000183          0.197
## 2 Porites rus        0.0179    0.214             0.358

This can be shown graphically. In the first version of this plot, you are only looking at caged P. rus. In the second version, you are seeing all corals in the experiment

Isotopes and growth

Now, instead of growing faster because the corals were photosynthesizing more, perhaps the corals were instead feeding more heterotrophically. We test this with 13C, which represents how much more 13C is in the host tissue versus the symbiont.

## # A tibble: 2  4
##   Species           P_Value Marginal_R2 Conditional_R2
##   <chr>               <dbl>       <dbl>          <dbl>
## 1 Pocillopora acuta   0.764     0.00472        0.00472
## 2 Porites rus         0.158     0.0998         0.0998

NOPE, and we can see this graphically:

## Warning: Removed 104 rows containing missing values or values outside the scale range
## (`geom_point()`).

Both

Since neither relationship is clean, it might be because they are explaining seperate parts of the variation in the growth data. For example, if the variables are not collinear (and thus whatever is driving corals eating is different than whatever is driving increases in symbiont populations), then it is possible that both are contributing to the variation in this dataset.

## # A tibble: 2  5
##   Species           P_Value_13C P_Value_symb Marginal_R2 Conditional_R2
##   <chr>                    <dbl>        <dbl>       <dbl>          <dbl>
## 1 Pocillopora acuta        0.759        0.655      0.0148         0.0148
## 2 Porites rus              0.386        0.297      0.130          0.182

Still no! It looks like neither is a good explainer of variation in the growth data.

What does this mean

The normal understanding of coral biology is that increases in symbiont populations or in heterotrophy should bring in more energy to the host, and therein increase growth; however, we are not seeing these relationships hold up when the coral fragments were introduced to SGD.

This can also be shown through basic correlation plots of the repsonse variables. I like this version from Performance Analytics:

Here, for P. rus:

or for P.acuta:

Next, I will explore what aspects of the gradient are effecting these response variables to gain a deeper understanding of coral holobiont response to SGD.

But first, lets explore the correlation of the explanatory variables:
